{
  "doc_id": "21722",
  "text": "However, preterm babies have an increased risk of respiratory distress syndrome (RDS) and the risk is even higher in elective cesarean section than in induced vaginal delivery [CITATION_1] . In addition, maternal cholestasis may predispose the newborn to unexpected respiratory distress syndrome [CITATION_2] . Zecca et al. concluded that the incidence of RDS in newborns from cholestatic pregnancies was twice as high as in the reference population. They hypothesized that bile acids can produce surfactant depletion in the alveoli [CITATION_3] so the risks and benefits of preterm delivery must be considered individually. Also Bacq et al. concluded in their meta-analysis that UDCA therapy might benefit fetal outcomes [CITATION_4] . It reduces fetal distress and fewer neonates in intensive care unit.",
